      <h2>Battery Pack</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Make sure the tool is in the OFF position before inserting the battery pack. If the release tabs are cracked or damaged, do not use the pack &mdash; it can fall out during operation.
      </div>

      <h3>Inserting and Releasing</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>To insert:</strong> align the battery and slide it into the tool until it locks into position. Do not force.</li>
        <li><strong>To release:</strong> press both battery release tabs (2) and pull the battery out.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Installing &amp; Removing Bits</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always remove the battery pack from the tool before removing or installing bits or accessories.
      </div>

      <p>The bit shank and collet should be clean and free of dust, wood residue, and grease before assembly.</p>

      <div class="image-row">
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p08_13.png" alt="Spindle locking bar pulled out to the marking arrow on the housing, with the spindle in one of its six 60-degree lock positions" />
          <figcaption>Fig. 2 &mdash; Engaging the spindle lock</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p08_14.png" alt="Collet wrench loosening the collet nut at the bottom of the router with a router bit shank inserted into the collet chuck" />
          <figcaption>Fig. 3 &mdash; Loosening the collet nut and inserting the bit</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Installing a Router Bit</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Press and hold the depth-adjustment button (8) to raise the router unit as high as possible from the base.</li>
        <li>Pull out the spindle locking bar (7) up to the marking arrow (6) on the housing. If needed, turn the spindle by hand until it locks (six lock positions offset by 60&deg;).</li>
        <li>Use the 17 mm collet wrench (18) to loosen the collet nut (9) counter-clockwise as viewed from the bottom of the router.</li>
        <li>Insert the bit shank (17) fully into the collet chuck, then back it out until the cutters are about 1/8" to 1/4" from the collet nut face. The shank must be inserted at least 5/8" for proper grip and minimal run-out.</li>
        <li>With the spindle lock engaged, firmly tighten the collet nut clockwise (as viewed from the bottom) with the wrench.</li>
        <li>Push the spindle locking bar (7) back into the disengaged position.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="warning">
        To prevent damage to the tool, never tighten the collet without a bit installed.
      </div>

      <h3>Removing a Router Bit</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Pull out the spindle locking bar (7) up to the marking arrow (6); turn the spindle by hand to lock it if needed.</li>
        <li>Loosen the collet nut (9) counter-clockwise with the wrench.</li>
        <li>Continue turning the collet chuck assembly until it pulls the collet (15) free from the spindle (16) and the bit (17) can be removed. The collet chuck is self-extracting &mdash; do <em>not</em> strike it.</li>
      </ol>

      <h2>Collet Chuck Care</h2>

      <p>
        Occasionally blow out the collet chuck with compressed air and clean the taper in the spindle
        shaft with a tissue or fine brush. The collet chuck is two parts that snap together; verify the
        collet (15) is properly seated in the collet nut (9), then lightly thread the chuck back onto the
        spindle. Replace worn or damaged collet chucks immediately.
      </p>

      <div class="image-row">
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p09_00.png" alt="Exploded detail of the collet chuck showing the collet seated in the collet nut and threading onto the router spindle" />
          <figcaption>Figs. 4 &amp; 5 &mdash; Collet, collet nut, and spindle assembly</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Operation</h2>

      <h3>Turning the Tool On and Off</h3>
      <p>Make sure the spindle locking bar (7) is in the disengaged position.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>ON:</strong> slide the On/Off switch (5) down so "I" appears.</li>
        <li><strong>OFF:</strong> slide the On/Off switch (5) up so "O" appears.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Setting the Depth of Cut</h3>

      <div class="warning">
        Adjust the depth of cut only with the motor switched off. Remove the battery pack and make sure the switch (5) is in the "O" (off) position.
      </div>

      <div class="image-row">
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p10_29.png" alt="Depth-of-cut locking wheel and adjustment button on the side of the palm router, used to unlock and lower the router to the desired depth" />
          <figcaption>Fig. 6 &mdash; Depth-of-cut locking wheel, adjustment button, and thumbwheel</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p10_32.png" alt="Fixing screw being threaded into the depth-of-cut adjustment thumbwheel with a flat-head screwdriver to fix the cutting depth" />
          <figcaption>Fig. 7 &mdash; Fixing the set depth with the fixing screw</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Install the desired router bit.</li>
        <li>Place the router on the workpiece.</li>
        <li>Turn the depth-of-cut locking wheel (14) counter-clockwise about half a revolution to unlock the adjustment.</li>
        <li>Press the depth-adjustment button (8) and slowly lower the router to approximately the desired depth, then release the button.</li>
        <li>Use the thumbwheel (10) to set the exact depth. Each revolution changes the cutting depth by 0.04" (1 mm).</li>
        <li>Turn the locking wheel (14) clockwise to securely lock the adjustment.</li>
        <li>Insert the battery pack and verify with a trial cut; re-adjust if needed (remove the battery first).</li>
        <li>To keep the tool fixed at the set depth, thread the fixing screw (11) into the thumbwheel (10) using a flat-head screwdriver with a maximum 5/32" (4 mm) blade width.</li>
      </ol>

