      <h3>Temperature Control / Overload Protection</h3>
      <p>The red LED (3) protects the battery and drive against overheating and overload:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Solid red:</strong> the battery or drive is too hot and the tool switches off automatically. Set the switch (5) to "O" and let the tool cool before resuming.</li>
        <li><strong>Flashing red:</strong> the tool is jammed and switches off. Set the switch to "O," remove the tool from the workpiece, and unlock the spindle locking bar (7) if needed. Once the spindle turns freely again, you can switch the tool back on.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Feeding the Router</h2>

      <p>
        In addition to the main gripping area (13), the base has Bosch-exclusive finger support pockets (20)
        for extra stability. Always hold the router with both hands, keep fingers away from the bit, and
        place both finger pockets over the workpiece so you can see your fingers and thumb at all times.
      </p>

      <div class="danger">
        Never hold the tool in unsafe ways (see Figs. 9 &amp; 10). Contact with a rotating bit can cause serious injury.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p11_00.png" alt="Correct two-handed grip on the palm router with both finger support pockets placed over the workpiece, contrasted with incorrect grips" />
        <figcaption>Fig. 8 &mdash; Proper two-handed grip using the finger support pockets</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Feed Direction</h3>
      <p>
        Viewed from the top, the bit (17) turns clockwise. The most efficient cut feeds the router so the bit
        turns <em>into</em> the workpiece, not away. Feed smoothly and steadily without forcing. Always hold
        the router off the workpiece when switching on or off: contact the work only after full speed is
        reached, and remove it before switching off.
      </p>

      <div class="image-row">
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p12_00.png" alt="Diagram of proper router feed direction relative to bit rotation for inside and outside edge cuts" />
          <figcaption>Fig. 11 &mdash; Proper feed direction for various cuts</figcaption>
        </div>
        <div class="figure">
          <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p12_02.png" alt="Self-piloted router bit with an integral ball-bearing pilot riding against the work surface to control horizontal cutting depth" />
          <figcaption>Fig. 12 &mdash; Self-piloted bit with bearing</figcaption>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3>Rate of Feed</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Regulate depth of cut and feed rate to keep the motor at high speed.</li>
        <li>Soft materials require a faster feed than hard materials.</li>
        <li>For large cuts, make several passes of increasing depth to avoid overloading the motor.</li>
        <li>Use bits with the shortest cutting length necessary to minimize run-out and chatter.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>If the router is hard to control, heats up, runs slowly, or leaves an imperfect cut, consider:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Wrong feed direction &mdash; hard to control.</li>
        <li>Feeding too fast &mdash; overloads the motor.</li>
        <li>Dull bit &mdash; overloads the motor.</li>
        <li>Cut too large for one pass &mdash; overloads the motor.</li>
        <li>Feeding too slow &mdash; leaves friction burns on the work.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Self-Piloted Bits</h3>
      <p>
        Self-piloted bits have an integral round tip or ball bearing that rides against the work surface to
        control horizontal cutting depth &mdash; no roller or straight guide is needed. When guiding against a
        laminated surface, use wax or another lubricant and avoid excess pressure. Keep bearing pilots clean
        and free of adhesive; replace bearings when they no longer turn freely. Maximum workpiece dimensions
        for edge/profile routing:
      </p>
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Material</th><th>Radius</th><th>Chamfer</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Hardwood</td><td>3/8" / 10 mm</td><td>1/4" / 6 mm</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Softwood</td><td>1/2" / 12 mm</td><td>3/8" / 10 mm</td></tr>
          <tr><td>MDF sheets</td><td>1/2" / 12 mm</td><td>3/8" / 10 mm</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plastic</td><td>1/2" / 12 mm</td><td>3/8" / 10 mm</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Plywood sheets</td><td>3/8" / 10 mm</td><td>1/4" / 6 mm</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Always disconnect the battery from the tool before cleaning or performing maintenance. Preventive maintenance by unauthorized personnel can misplace internal wires and create a serious hazard &mdash; have all service done by a Bosch Factory Service Center or Authorized Bosch Service Station.
      </div>

      <h3>Cleaning</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>Keep ventilation openings and the switch lever clean and free of foreign matter. Do not insert pointed objects through the openings.</li>
        <li>Clean the tool with a vacuum, paintbrush, or hand brush after use, and keep the guide columns free of wood dust.</li>
        <li>Apply a drop of lubricant to the smooth guide column (19).</li>
        <li>Do not use gasoline, carbon tetrachloride, chlorinated solvents, ammonia, or ammonia-based detergents &mdash; they damage plastic parts.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/bosch-gkf12v-25n/p13_00.png" alt="Applying a drop of lubricant to the smooth guide column of the palm router during cleaning and maintenance" />
        <figcaption>Fig. 13 &mdash; Lubricating the smooth guide column (19)</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Bearings, Batteries &amp; Motor</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Bearings:</strong> replace noisy bearings at once to avoid overheating or motor failure.</li>
        <li><strong>Batteries:</strong> watch for packs nearing end of life. Decreased performance or shorter run time between charges means it is time to replace the pack.</li>
        <li><strong>Motor:</strong> have the motor examined every six months to maintain peak efficiency. Use only a genuine Bosch replacement motor designed for this tool.</li>
      </ul>

